title.narrative: 401 STRENGTHENING PREVENTIVE AND RESPONSIVE CP SYSTEMS

description.narrative: By 2022, child protection systems and structures have adequate human and financial resources, institutional capacity, monitoring and data management ability in selected states to deliver preventive and responsive child protection service, which contributes to Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

title.narrative: By 2022, child protection systems and structures have adequate human and financial resources, institutional capacity, monitoringand data management ability in selected states to deliver preventive and responsive child protection service

description.narrative: Through UNICEF support, Child Protection Systems have been strengthened in 17 States, with 215,753 child protection functionaries and allied workers (45% female) capacitated, an increase of 37.7% from 2020, resulting in 1,138,551 women, girls and boys accessing gender-based violence risk mitigation, prevention, and response. UNICEF’s continued advocacy efforts on social service workforce strengthening resulted in recruitment and closing of the vacancy gaps. In 17 states, MHPSS services were scaled up to reach 661,071 children (46% girls); an increase of 83% in comparison to 2020 through institutionalized capacity strengthening, advocacy and multi-sectoral intervention with health, nutrition, and education sectors. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:06/01/2022
